"How do you know if your story-game is any good?

Not from the same feeling that told you 'this is my idea, I love it.'
Not from running through it yourself — you know it too well. You
know only from watching someone play who has never seen it.

This appendix is the playtest protocol. Twenty questions to ask.
Body-language cues to watch for. What patterns mean, and what to
do about them.

---

## The setup

Get a friend. Sit next to them. Do not touch the keyboard. Do not
talk unless they ask a direct question. Watch. Take notes silently.

Ideal duration: 30-45 minutes. Long enough that they get past the
opening; short enough that they don't get exhausted. If your game
is longer than 45 minutes, run playtests in chunks — 'today just
the first act.'

Bring water. Playtesting is thirsty work for the tester.

---

## What to watch (body language)

**They lean forward.** They are engaged. The scene is working.

**They lean back.** They are bored. The scene is not working.

**They smile.** A moment of pleasure. Note when. That is a moment to
protect and multiply.

**They frown.** Confusion or displeasure. Note what just happened.

**They look at their phone.** You have lost them. The next minute
had better re-engage them.

**They fidget.** Waiting for something. Your pace is off.

**They mouth the words.** They are reading intently. Good.

**They stop reading.** They are thinking about what they read. Also
good — but do not follow up with three more lines immediately. Let
the moment breathe.

**They laugh.** Note it. Laughs are gold.

**They cry.** Note it. Do not comment. Bring tissues.

---

## After the play — twenty questions

Ask these in order. Do not skip. Do not soften.

### Structure

1. **Which ending did you get?**
   (Ensures they finished. Also tells you which endings players
   gravitate toward.)

2. **Roughly how long did you play?**
   (Their perception, not clock time. If it felt longer than it
   was, pacing is slow. If shorter, pacing is fast.)

3. **Was there a chapter or scene that felt too long?**
   (Direct feedback on pacing bottlenecks.)

4. **Was there a chapter or scene that felt too short?**
   (Often the emotional peaks. If they wanted more, that's a
   signal you had them.)

### Attention

5. **What was the moment you felt most alive?**
   (The scene that made them lean forward, laugh, or cry. This is
   the load-bearing moment of your game.)

6. **Where did you get bored?**
   (The scene where they leaned back. Sometimes multiple. All are
   fixable.)

7. **Did you ever want to quit?**
   (If yes, where? That's where the design is failing them.)

### Choices

8. **Was there a choice that felt fake — like it didn't matter?**
   (Consequence-table failure. Check that choice's downstream
   references.)

9. **Was there a choice you wanted to make but couldn't?**
   (Missing option. Sometimes worth adding.)

10. **Did you feel the game respected your choices?**
    (Vague, but their feeling matters more than the answer's
    precision.)

### Characters

11. **Who was your favorite character? Why?**
    (Watch what they name. Often it's not who you expected.)

12. **Who did you not like? Why?**
    (Not the villain. If they don't like the villain, that's fine.
    If they don't like someone you wanted them to bond with,
    problem.)

13. **Was there a character you wanted to see more of?**
    (Might be a character who should have had a bigger role.)

14. **Was there a character you wanted to see less of?**
    (Might be a character taking up screen time without earning
    it.)

### Feel

15. **Did the game feel like reading, watching, or playing?**
    (No wrong answer, but tells you what genre-analog they
    perceived. Your intent should match.)

16. **What was the tone of the game — light, heavy, funny, sad?**
    (Their perception vs. your intent. Mismatch means voice
    tuning needed.)

17. **Was there anything that felt like a system rather than a
    story?**
    (Ideally no. If yes, that's where your seams are showing.)

### Companion (if applicable)

18. **Did you talk to the [old woman / companion character]?**
    (Zero-answer means she is invisible; frequent-answer means
    she is being useful.)

19. **Did she interrupt at a bad time?**
    (Any yes here means you're triggering her at the wrong
    beats.)

20. **Would you replay this game?**
    (The ultimate question. Not 'did you like it' but 'would you
    do it again.' A yes here means you have made something they
    care about.)

---

## Analyzing the answers

**Convergence.** If three friends give the same answer to a question,
that is a REAL signal. Fix it or protect it.

**Divergence.** If three friends give different answers, the game is
Rorschach-shaped for that dimension. Neither good nor bad
necessarily — but be curious.

**Silence.** If a friend can't remember something (a character, a
choice, a scene), it did not land. Either strengthen it or cut it.

**Enthusiasm.** If they get animated talking about a scene, protect
that scene. Do not touch it. Build outward.

---

## Common findings and their fixes

**'I got bored in the middle.'**
Middle acts sag naturally. Add a peak at the midpoint — a small
revelation, a new character, a scene of unexpected texture.

**'The choices didn't feel like they mattered.'**
Consequence-table failure. Go back to appendix I. Add downstream
references to the choices they mentioned.

**'I didn't understand what to do at [scene X].'**
Missing signposting. Add a small hint in-scene or via the
companion.

**'That character was boring.'**
Body-language check. Does the character have a signature (breath
rate, sway, expression baseline)? If they are just standing still,
they are furniture. See appendix C.

**'The ending felt sudden.'**
Missing setup. Track backward: which scenes were meant to prepare
the ending? Are they doing enough?

**'The ending felt unearned.'**
Player expected a reward for effort. Endings should honor what the
player did, not just what the writer felt like writing.

**'It was too short.'**
Success. Do not artificially extend. Trust the impact of a short
game.

**'It was too long.'**
Cut. Every scene should earn its screen time. Cut the ones that
don't.

---

## The correctness question

'What does correct mean for narrative?'

Not the same as correctness for code. There is no unit test for a
scene. But some heuristics:

**A scene is correct if the emotion the writer intended is the
emotion the player felt.** Playtest reveals this. Alignment good;
misalignment bad.

**A scene is correct if the player can navigate it.** They know
what to do; they can execute; they see the result. Confusion is
correctness failure.

**A scene is correct if it earns its runtime.** A three-minute
scene that could be a thirty-second scene is not correct. Cut.

**A scene is correct if it connects to what came before and prepares
what comes next.** A scene disconnected from the arc is not
correct even if it is beautifully written.

Correctness in narrative is about function AND feeling. Both matter.

---

## After the fix — a second playtest

Get a DIFFERENT friend. Play through the fixed version. Watch
whether the fixed scene works.

Do not use the same friend twice for the same version. They already
know the story; their reactions are contaminated.

Rotating playtesters means every playtest gives fresh signal.

---

## Playtest ethics

**Never argue with a playtester.** Their experience is their
experience. Your intent is not their experience. Take the data.

**Never make them feel bad about their answers.** They are doing
you a favor. Their honest answers are more valuable than their
polite answers.

**Never ask them to play again if they didn't want to.** If they
finished and they're done, thank them and let them go.

**Thank them specifically.** 'I noticed you leaned forward at the
scene with the fisherman — that helped me a lot.' Specific thanks
means you were paying attention. They will play for you again.

---

## Solo playtest — the reset

You cannot playtest your own game with fresh eyes. But you can
approximate it.

Wait three weeks. Come back. Read the game as if you have not
seen it. Notice where you get bored. Notice where you smile.

This is not as good as a real playtester, but it is better than
nothing.

Do not do this the day after you wrote the game. You will just
replay your own intent.

---

## Summary

Playtest with real people. Twenty questions. Watch body language.
Convergence is signal; divergence is Rorschach; silence is failure.
Common findings have common fixes. Never argue with a tester;
thank them specifically.

The game that a playtester says 'I want to play again' is a game
worth shipping. Everything else is iteration.")
